Diet of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner of meatballs
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent being obese.
Obese children often come from unhealthy families, according to a recent survey.
Once again, the environment and patterns surrounding a child are vital to healthy human development.
For example, the incidence of bedbugs in obese children is up to half that in families with normal-weight children.
Fried fries were eaten for dinner the day before a research study linked to an awareness campaign called Obesity is no coincidence over 19 percent of obese people.
Also, while most families of today's schoolchildren do not have a habit of exercising in families of obese children, only 15 percent of the children said that their parents make time for physical activity at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 primary school children from all over the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the Obesity is Not a Chance event, sponsored by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students from grades 4 to 8 have been involved in the project.
A healthy diet and sufficient physical activity in the family are among the determining factors behind the dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the respondents said they ate five meals a day on the breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner diet, which is a basic requirement for proper nutrition", says one survey.
No breakfast and no dinner
Experts point out that even the relative details, such as regular family breakfast times, are essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of school families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding that 10 percent of the households didn't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the foundation of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families with obese children had a much higher incidence of eating unhealthy fries.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary sodas every day (70 percent).
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly participate in sports, their parents did less than half that - 15 percent.
Make up your own menu
The second part of the survey allowed the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own menus according to their own tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition".
Their favorite foods include many flour, meat, and sweet foods.
"The particular concern is the high popularity of sugary lemonades", says the final report of the survey.
For lunch, pasta was the main course, just ahead of chicken.
But the kids didn't want any legumes at all, and the fish and lunch vegetable food is low.
Health-related
The study also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if given the right information.
"It is no coincidence that a control group of survey participants who completed a questionnaire after the Obesity Education Lecture showed a significant shift in preferences towards healthy eating in a number of cases", the project results state.
The most striking example was in the case of lemonade, where more children would start to prefer plain water.
Children were also much more likely to check poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and to limit sweet foods and dumplings.
