So it's not really a bug, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story in which the protagonist, Jack, has certain personal character problems and as a solution, he is offered participation in an illegal race across America.
You're gonna get behind the wheel of a car on the west coast in San Francisco and your job is to get to New York first.
The idea has some interesting elements.
The circuit is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
This means that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't get the feeling for a second that the game's always the same.
Some of the environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of graphics matches previous installments in the series.
So it's not a big deal.
But driving through deserts, autumn landscapes, or high in snow-capped mountains is visually very pleasing.
And the races are occasionally colored by some unusual element.
For example, in the desert, you get caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to be swept away by an avalanche.
Besides, the individual races are pretty well lined up.
There's only a few types, but that's enough.
You try to outrun the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up with time (a classic stop-gap fight), and then you're faced with a duel with a single opponent.
