Brand story:
IBM's innovator enters its second century of existence
If someone were looking for the word that best describes IBM's strategy, the closest one would probably be "long-term".
To the general public, IBM is a symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is seen as very contemporary, and yet it has been 100 years since its founding.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by the company's first president, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already made the slogan that many of the world's problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant would unfold (and also the name of the internal magazine that began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully constructed corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement toward the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a century because it stayed true to its core values while not being afraid to change everything else around it.
