The history of IBM: From cheese cutters to space flights
IBM was founded in New York City over a hundred years ago, originally under the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 - originally a trademark used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1880s.
They had technology like the famous "pipes", clocks that recorded employees' arrivals and departures.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also served as chairman of the company's board of directors until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still the building blocks of an unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began by manufacturing and selling all kinds of business machines - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years Watson was at the helm, the company doubled its turnover to $9 million and began a massive expansion into all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost 40 years in the executive chair, his son, Thomas Watson, Jr., succeeded him.
Under his leadership, IBM began work on artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM humans and computers helped NASA pilot missions to Mercury, Saturn, and the famous 1969 manned moon landing.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "piece of cake" that set the computer standard of the day, the IBM 5150 came out in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to focus on consulting and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off for the last three years is the concept of a Smarter Planet.
It aims to make smart use of technology in areas not yet planned and to improve conditions, for example, in transport and urban management.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which helps retailers manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history at home.
It established its branch in what was then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe Centre is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team on voice recognition.
