How fares have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state-owned travel agencies were authorised in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold only tours to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists thus went on holiday to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks too) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but you had to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" at the travel agency.
But it wasn't won anyway.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition of travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange pledge it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for travel to the West.
However, by far the most common holiday was spent in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of huts and cottages being built by the Czechs, a practice that survives to this day.
Travel in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our top priorities until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The enormous paradox, which we no longer realize, is that Croatia, which is now our most popular country, was not free to travel to until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia.
As early as the early 1990s, visa requirements for neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna, Austria, and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to see it for a while.
For example, in Paris, we slept in tents during Czech trips to parks because our income at the time did not allow us to afford a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of traveling Czechs at this time was to bring their own food, canned goods, salami, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech króna, which finally allowed our tourists to buy Western currency freely after many decades.
But our living standards and, with them, average wages were rising, leading to another important moment in 1997.
The increase in demand for travel has led to the regular introduction of charter flights by travel agents since 1997, which have made flights incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of booking volume discounts.
By the late 1990's, the Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries except the United States, which made our travels easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when due to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotics was made from the Czech Republic to Thailand.
From this year, direct charter flights to warm far-flung countries will be launched with Czech tourists every year.
The exotic country is now visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States cancelled visas for Czech tourists, and our country was definitively ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and spent more than CZK 15 000 per person on a single holiday abroad including the cost of accommodation.
