A massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund's new, emotionally charged book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, opens with a list of characters so long that you'll feel dizzy.
A suggestion for you to make at this time is to carefully tear out this page and make a bookmark.
Because you'll get to know all the characters in Mr. Englund's novel very well, and this list will serve as a navigation - a kind of beacon - for you at times when, like the men and women in the story, you feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new vice president of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are discussing is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "an antihistorical work".
It contains several very famous names, important treaties or famous battles, but it is almost devoid of ambassadors, energetic journalists and discussions of tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as a "book about what it was like".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the wartime experiences of 20 men and women, more or less a dozen, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, become crippled, go mad, or die.
Their lives flickering like the flames of a church candle - new ones being added to the web of destiny while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It corrects the notion that World War I was all about the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book deal with problems of being hit by a beehive, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of a pyramid, or dealing with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it's been a very moving read.
War will consume people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
If you hear cannon fire in the distance and you're a woman at home with your children, will you run or stay?
Who's that coming?
Almost no one understands what's happening, even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts", noted Mr. Englund, "was filled by speculation, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are largely taken from biographies, letters, and other published material.
Their descriptions of life may sound intimidating and captivating, but the inclusion of minute moments and details makes them completely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Substitute, substitute everywhere".
"Coffee topping, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons, and so on".
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheep fat (and supplemented with a fake wooden bone), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes for sausage and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American, finding his inner drive for savagery and brutality, declares about war: "You will finally understand that this is human nature, not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey and the evening paper or a good book and pretend that this mask of yours represents civilization and that behind this starchy self there is no barbarian".
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon, and no one will notice, let alone mourn.
"When one finally accepts the sacrifice, one would at least expect it to be done before the eyes of an appreciative audience", he writes.
Instead, he feels like a "convict being hung in secret".
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the rise of new terrors.
"Conflict increasingly became economic competition and a competitive struggle", writes Mr. Englund, "a war between factories".
He caught what he calls "a new kind of beast of the coming century: a vocal and ideologically sworn mass murderer in tailored clothes who carries out his bloodletting without leaving the table".
People act completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a sexually transmitted disease from prostitutes to avoid serving in the front.
"The most egregious example of this was the trade in gonorrhoea pus, which soldiers bought and rubbed on their genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital", he writes.
"The most desperate of them rubbed it in their eyes, often blinded them for the rest of their lives".
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is lively but not flashy, which is a perfect fit for his human theme.
In dozens of small outputs, he shows how the war "unleashed forces beyond our control: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books on World War I usually worked with hints rather than a comprehensive narrative, such as Paul Fussell's World War I and Modern Memory or novels like Erich Maria Remarque's All Quiet on the Western Front.
Mr Englund prefers an unconventional concept.
