After the tragedy this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy - just go to Facebook.
"We've realised that getting them is not really that hard", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The Facebook database of personal information is so extensive, Bartlett says, that researchers simply used the site's advertising to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for with absolute accuracy - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, and they targeted them and sent them ads, but instead of inviting them to join newly formed groups or offering them diet products, they asked them to fill out a questionnaire that asked questions about their education level, their attitude to violence and their optimism about their own future.
Using Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever leaving their offices.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men, dismayed by the rising rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who remain hidden behind a computer screen".
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and policy researchers use these sites to study everything from health issues to hidden social trends to status updates, wall posts and "like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users, each providing an average of three different pieces of data per day, making the social network an "information supernova" that is behind many new research projects.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"It used to be that if you wanted to do a poll of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You have to get to a side where they'd never let you in", says Bartlett.
"Facebook is breaking down all of that - you just go right to them".
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a public health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that college students who shared their drinking habits on Facebook were at a much higher risk of developing alcoholism than students who kept quiet about the subject.
Moren suggests that students' peers monitor the site and come forward with an offer of help to a student who posts too many drunken status updates.
"You can't fix a problem if you can't diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Morenova's study and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We found a way to identify vulnerable children we otherwise wouldn't have a chance to find".
Facebook itself is constantly probing its users' data.
The site's information team compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010, and the nation's satisfaction ratio (mostly using information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its information treasury available for research by others).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, they have to give the site their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clear rules about how to collect data offline, but online data is available to everyone.
"I don't think most users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using his students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they thought that information was only between them and their friends".
The question of methodology is also to be considered next.
Even when you do research offline, there's no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There's no way to verify how much of the information on the Facebook profile and the posts on the wall are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, feels that pencil and notebook remain the best possible tools to use in research.
