As soon as Steve Jobs died on October 5th, opinions began to emerge that compared him to Henry Ford - and elected him for his genius as the greatest modern inventor.
In the recently rediscovered interview with Jobs, which was dusted for a special movie that's heading to theaters this week, it will be for all Apple fans to know that his creative mind was perfectly aware of the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was a brilliant designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a man who took every little thing to the last detail - believing that many entrepreneurs suffer from "the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work . . . [but] there is still a long way to go between a great idea and a great finished product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was working on the TV show Triumph of the Computer Crazies, which was about the dawn of personal computers.
By this time, it had been ten years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company NeXT, and he was eager to see the Internet embraced by the general public.
The TV show ended up using only a brief portion of the entire interview with Cringely, and original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
However, shortly after Jobs' death, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
This is the footage, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: Lost Interview, which will be released in select theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who's notoriously reluctant to give long interviews, here Jobs seems surprisingly excited to be able to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
And he also turns out to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during the interview, there's a long pause between the question and the answer -- 10 to 15 seconds of thought, where you see how Jobs thinks his answer through perfectly to be as relevant and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, when he acts impatient when Cringley asks questions, and rushes him to get to more important issues and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, and it contains some frighteningly prophetic thoughts as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing well and badly, while offering his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read a posthumous review of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here as a passionate dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
Before long, after he had expressed his ideas, he also began to put them into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"In my years in business, I've always asked, 'Why are you doing this?' and the answer has always been the same, 'Well, that's just the way it is.'"
No one knows why they do what they do, they never think deeply about business matters.
I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way costs were recorded - they often started with "standard costs", which he could only guess at, and at that point he decided to go his own way - he developed an automated tool that guaranteed that they could determine business costs in an instant.
How he did the Pope's spanking:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak -- a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
There's been a lot written about this device in the past, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as a tool of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a pay phone and had it beamed from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
"We've been around the world like this at least half a dozen times, so when we shouted something into the pay phone, it rang a minute later from the other phone at the door", Jobs laughs.
"We were young and we realized that we could build ourselves something that could run a billion-dollar infrastructure around the world".
The two of us built a tiny thing that could control a much bigger giant -- it was an incredible experience, and I don't think Apple would have ever been created without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a joke that he and Wozniak almost made, where they called the Vatican in the middle of the night using a Blue Box and asked if they could speak to the Pope, posing as Henry Kissinger.
Gradually, more and more high-ranking members of the Catholic Church were called in to speak with the American diplomat in the middle of the night, and just before the pope himself was awakened to the phone, the couple chuckled and hung up.
How he fell in love with technology (and talked to Bill Hewlett on the phone):
When he was 12 and looking for spare parts to build a meter, he found a number in the phone book for Bill Hewlett and called him.
Within 20 minutes of their conversation, Jobs had secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was an incredible influence on me, it was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how it should treat its employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research lab in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a CRT monitor, and I fell in love with it instantly.
As a teenager at HP, I was moving up the ranks, hanging around this computer and writing programs for it.
How he invents innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about how he's inventing new products while running.
Early in his career, when he was selling some circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble an entire computer for him.
He had only 30 days of paid time to design, assemble and deliver the finished device.
When he was later at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced developing the computer mouse:
"I remember we were having a pretty heated argument. They were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a $300 mouse], and I stopped having fun, so I went out and found a designer".
And 90 days later, we were able to build a perfectly reliable mouse for $15 dollars.
How big companies are running out of breath:
Long before he led the resurrection of Apple, Jobs presciently predicted that many industry leaders would falter in their vision and lose their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be a more successful company.
At that point, sales and marketing are in the air, so companies are run by people who are in charge of that, while people who are in charge of their own products are left out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius who led society to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned literally the entire computer industry.
It could be 10 times bigger than it is, it could be Microsoft in the '90s...
But instead of winning, they lost.
How he sees innovation as an art form:
"There's a long way to go and a lot of work to do between a great idea and a great finished product... and as that great idea evolves, it changes and grows".
You'll learn a lot about him in the meantime.
You have to make a lot of compromises -- some things you can't just make electrons, glass, robots or factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your head at all times -- different concepts -- and put them together...
It's ultimately about taste -- you try to think about the best things that humanity has ever created, and you kind of try to project them into what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
The reason the Macintosh company was so amazing and successful was because the people who worked on it were great musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and, incidentally, also the best computer experts in the world.
Without computers and new technologies, they would be doing amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas dining with health care opponents while their case was in court
On the day the Supreme Court convened behind closed doors to consider the politically contentious question of whether to accept an objection to President Obama's health care law, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a gala dinner sponsored by a law firm that will be sitting in the courtroom.
The incident occurred last Thursday when all nine judges met to discuss the motions.
One of the cases we discussed was a lawsuit brought by 26 states challenging a radical overhaul of health care that Congress passed last year - a law that has mobilized conservative activists around the world.
The judges agreed to hear the case, but a 5.5-hour hearing is expected in March, and the outcome will further fuel the presidential election, which is scheduled for 2012 and will be in full swing when the decision is made.
The lawyer who will appear in court and try to get the law struck down will most likely be Paul Clement, who served as the United States Attorney General under George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been advocating conservative legal principles for many years.
Another company that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the business associations challenging the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., for which huge sums of money are at stake in the case.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court hearing on the case.
Among those present was Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and a staunch opponent of the Affordable Care Act.
And the introduction of the guests?
This is nothing new: these two judges have been participating in Federalist Society events for years.
And it's certainly not anything that violates ethics.
In effect, these judges are exempt from the code of conduct that applies to lower federal judges.
If this were not the case, their conduct would certainly fall under Principle C4, which states that 'a judge may participate in events organised by related and other organisations for the purpose of raising funds, but he may not be a speaker, guest of honour or be featured on the programme of events.'
Yet Scalia and Thomas' relationship to the two law firms involved in the case, as well as the companies with a huge financial stake in the case, was rich enough to alarm activists calling for ethics in government.
"This shocking violation of ethics and disregard for the code of conduct contradicts several judges' claims that the Supreme Court follows the same rules as all other federal judges", said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"Judges have been drinking and dining at a benefit with lawyers awaiting trial".
Their presence and assistance in raising funds through this event undermines all claims of impartiality, which is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little understanding of their critics, telling them that they too had no problem combining their judicial duties with the actions of groups like the Federalist Society.
Thomas' wife Ginni is a high-ranking conservative activist.
And the conservatives argue that the ethical issue is with Justice Elena Kagan, not with Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was the attorney general under President Obama when the first objections to the law came before the court.
Kagan's critics are pressing her to drop the case, claiming she fought for the law too hard to be unbiased now.
Kagan has not indicated that she's going to resign.
Boeing has won a record $ 18 billion jet contract
Emirates Airlines has placed an order for 50 two-lane jetliners of the Boeing 777 family with the option to purchase 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Aman Air, for which it collects over USD 1 billion.
When a company gets an order for 50 of their products, it's usually no cause for celebration.
But if that company is the Boeing Co. and the price of these 50 planes is a record $18 billion, that's another story.
Equally important news is where Boeing got the contract from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine for future aircraft orders.
According to a forecast released Monday, the Chicago-based company estimates that airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 planes worth $450 billion over the next 20 years.
Boeing announced its largest ever order for a commercial airliner at the weekend, in terms of dollar value, 50 two-lane jetliners.
The sensational order came from Emirates airlines based in Dubai.
Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Air Show that the airlines have the option to purchase an additional 20 aircraft, bringing the total value of the order to USD 26 billion.
Then on Monday, Boeing announced that Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, sometimes called Dreamliners, which boast significantly improved fuel efficiency and passenger facilities.
The total cost of these six aircraft is over $1 billion.
"This is excellent news for Boeing as a whole", said Neal Dihora, an analyst for Morningstar.
"The quality of these particular customers is very high".
Many airlines in the Middle East are owned by oil-producing nations.
This means that they not only have the money to pay for the planes, but the increase in fuel prices - usually hurting the airlines because it's one of their biggest costs - is not as decisive because the country itself is profiting from higher oil prices.
This is important because they are not as likely as other airlines to cancel or postpone aircraft orders due to higher fuel prices, says Dihora.
"They have such natural protection", he says.
The order from Emirates strengthens Boeing's leading position in the wide-body market and puts Airbus SAS at a disadvantage as it sought to challenge Boeing's dominance with its A350 transport model.
Boeing's victory comes four months after Airbus officials announced that the first flight of their largest aircraft, the A350, a direct competitor to the 777-300ER, would be postponed.
The reason for the delay was that customers demanded a higher payload and range, so the manufacturer took time to provide more engine power.
The share price of Boeing Co increased by 1.5% to USD 67,94.
The president 's sister seems to have lost the election in Michoacan .
Luisa Maria Calderon claims that her opponent, Fausto Vallejon of the PRI, was helped by drug traffickers in his quest for the governorship.
Felipe Calderona's sister, who appeared to have lost a violent statewide election for governor in Michoacan, later claimed on Monday that drug traffickers helped one of her opponents win.
Preliminary results have awarded the leadership in the Western State governorship election to Faust Vallej of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
"The interference of members of organized crime in the entire electoral process and especially in the course of yesterday's elections is alarming not only for Michoacán but for our entire country", Luisa Maria Calderon said in a radio interview the day after Sunday's election.
"They threatened our candidates, members of our polling group... they confiscated the ballot boxes, they put up roadblocks... and they made people vote on the order of the PRI.
The PRI party ruled Mexico for seven decades until 2000, when it lost the presidency.
However, he plans to return to power soon, and winning the election in Michoacan is an important step in that effort.
The PRI hopes to win the presidential election in July.
It seems Vallejo beat Calderon, who was leading the day before the election, by a very narrow margin.
Calderon, the candidate for her brother's conservative National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejón as the winner.
In third place is Silvano Aureolis, the candidate of the left-wing Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, which has so far held the governorship, a very unfortunate defeat for a fractious and ill-fated party ahead of the 2012 presidential election.
Aureoles also refused to accept the preliminary results as valid.
Vallejo, former mayor of the state capital of Morelia, rejects any ties to drug traffickers and urges other candidates to recognize the results.
Michoacán has long been controlled by drug cartels specializing in marijuana, heroin and methamphetamine.
It is the home state of President Calderón, and it was in Michoacán that he launched a military campaign against smugglers in December 2006.
But the violence continued.
The mayor of the PAN party, a supporter of Luisa Maria Calderón, was assassinated just a week before the election and many candidates withdrew from the election out of fear.
But whatever the results of the Michoacan election look like for the PRI, a victory for the party will help to give it a new impetus.
The PRI's expected presidential candidate, Enrique Pena Nieto, of Washington congratulated Vallej, saying: "I think this victory could be very encouraging for the year ahead".
ADB calls on Asia to help save the eurozone
The Asian Development Bank has called on India and China to be ready to help bail out the eurozone from its severe debt crisis, otherwise an overall global economic downturn could ensue, with a negative impact on growth in Asia as well.
Rajat Nag, the managing director of the Manila-based ADB, said that the world's two fastest-growing economies must "do everything in their power" to help the currency bloc recover quickly through the International Monetary Fund, or direct bilateral agreements.
He warned that the BRICS [Brazil, Russia, India, China] were watching all of Europe's troubles "too unconcernedly", and said that Asian financial aid, combined with European leadership and resources, would help avert a long-term collapse of the global economy.
"We're all in this together".
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful", he told the Financial Times during an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be protected to some extent, but it is certainly not immune".
"So if China and India can help, they should definitely do it".
The European Monetary Union has been severely tested by a serious debt crisis for several months.
In recent days, Italy's borrowing costs have risen dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The growing debt crisis in Europe has raised concerns that it could drag the global economy back into recession, and calls have begun to emerge for the emerging leading economies to come together and help the euro area find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that all Asian aid would be channelled through the IMF, but noted that bilateral aid - such as the purchase of bonds from the European Union Financial Assistance Fund, the European institution for financial stability - would provide greater bargaining power for Asian partners of European countries.
Anand Sharma, India's commerce minister, said that "India will do what it can" to help the Eurozone, as its own economy now suffers from declining exports and a drying of foreign capital.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and unrestful", he said.
"We are faced with a difficult task and we must maintain a high growth rate".
"This is not an alternative, this is a fact, because otherwise we would not be able to find jobs for tens of millions of our young men and women".
Others argue that emerging economies, such as India's, have little to help European economies when they are forced to face their own serious economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said it would be politically very difficult to explain aid to Europe to India's 1.2 billion people, 800 million of whom live on $2 a day or less.
"One day they might find that Greeks retire at 50 and enjoy beach holidays, which they would find hard to explain", he noted.
Lee Howell, Director General of the World Economic Forum, similarly questioned why Indian reserves should be used to maintain well-paid jobs for many Greek citizens in poorly managed and loss-making sectors such as rail transport.
Mr Nag stressed that the eurozone crisis was threatened by a 'dangerous domino effect'.
The Bank's forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia between 2011 and 2012 now faces a "downside risk" due to the European threat.
He said that vulnerable emerging markets must develop "unpredictable spending plans" to protect themselves from a downturn and a significant outflow of capital from their economies.
Pentagon warns of possible defense cuts
Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta has given Congress a big push on Monday when he warned that looming automatic budget cuts could threaten national security and trigger a financial chain reaction starting at the Pentagon and continuing through the battlefields of Afghanistan to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon will already have to spend $450 billion in budget cuts over the next decade, but now it fears another $600 billion if Congress fails to reach a spending agreement.
"The effects of these cuts would be devastating to the entire department", Panetta wrote in a letter to Senators John McCain, Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to agree on a budget and the resulting so-called moratorium would cause a 23% flat rate cut and halt many new projects.
"Because of such a huge cut, used in this reckless way, it will not be possible to carry out most of our shipbuilding or ship projects - you cannot buy only three-quarters of the buildings or ships.
"We will also be forced to separate many of our civilian employees, and since the reduction is to take place so quickly, we will almost certainly also have to put civilians on forced leave to be able to meet target requirements".
"These changes could shake the faith of those who care for our military and seriously damage its readiness".
Eventually, the cuts will affect combat troops, Panetta said.
"While the accounts for financing possible war operations overseas will not be directly affected by this halt, operations there will be negatively affected by major changes in other budgets", warned Panetta.
"There will be cuts in contract personnel as well, which will result in a delay in the contractual agreements that support our people's war effort".
'The status of paid staff will be reduced, which will also result in late payments to suppliers and a consequent disruption of legal and political support.'
Both senators wrote Panett back ten days ago, asking for details regarding the possible impact of automatic cuts at the Department of Defense.
"The consequences of the shutdown at the Department of Defense could cause a rapid degradation of the image of the United States as a world military power".
"We are strictly against this drastic measure", the senators announced in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they released Panetta's letter.
"It's not an agreement we can live with, and we certainly don't want to sign it".
"The planned cuts are a threat to the national security of the United States, which we should not allow".
"It remains to be seen whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings will increase pressure on Congress to approve the budget and amplify calls to remove the Pentagon from the list of areas of restricted use.
Panetta has been increasingly open in recent days to talk about possible cuts, even though he himself had moved to his senior position at the Pentagon with years of experience approving budgets in Congress and the White House, so he knew he was going to be in a tough fight.
At a press conference held last week, the Secretary of Defense hinted at a brief picture of what his department can expect - an army shell, but one that lacks a core.
"It'll be like a ship without sailors".
"It'll be like a brigade without ammunition".
"It'll be like an air force without trained pilots".
"It will be like a paper tiger, like an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to complete the mission", Panetta said at the start of his speech at the Pentagon.
"He will be like a unit with no morale, unprepared and unable to face a potential enemy".
"As a result, aggression will be welcomed... "
In an appendix to the letter to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifies how the reduction will result in "significant operational risks: delayed response to crises, conflicts and disasters; significantly reduced options for landings and deployments worldwide; anticipated unacceptable risk in future combat operations".
Panetta added that some of the largest defense projects could be waiting to be completed, including those already being tested and those in the early planning stages.
Among the items on the list were the F-35 project, a planned new bomber, a new generation of ballistic submarines, a new coastal warship, and a new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy wanted to replace the Humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 would save $80 billion over the next decade, but its proponents say it is a necessary next step in the military upgrade needed to deal with potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Tell a Lie
A glance at recent headlines reveals just how prevalent and pervasive lying and deception are in our daily lives.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy with the sexual harassment allegations against several women - both sides claiming the latter is a lie.
Penn State administrators were accused of perjury when they tried to cover up a record of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught with a microphone on telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
A lie has been able to destroy entire careers and undermine the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing campaign funds to try to cover up his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that swept Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual attraction to Monica Lewinsky.
There are stories of cheating in schools and colleges all over the place.
There are instances when teachers themselves give their students test answers just to look good in their own assessments.
Mentors who are supposed to teach the opposite send a message that lying and deceit are acceptable.
How many scams do we see?
Studies show that you lie anywhere from 10 to 200 times in a single day.
Let's assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study found that strangers lie three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting someone.
Lying detection, or "discovery of lies", is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it's not a social game that's like, say, a charade where you yell, "I've got you". Deception recognition is a serious branch of science that works with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities through detailed research projects, especially in psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're just hanging out, or cocktailing, or blushing, or flirting.
Do not conclude, however, that it is somehow difficult to spot and detect a liar.
A trained lie detector can detect truth from sentence structure, tiny facial expressions, the way questions are formulated and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from the vast and growing field of lie detection, and it is clear that lie detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can be very helpful in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or managing people.
Good liars are also good at reading others, letting them soak in their alertness, directing their emotions, and intuitively sensing how the other party is receiving them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "personal" lies - mostly to protect one's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than single people (but the lies they tell are usually "disgraceful").
We also know that if you're perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know when someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's normal behavior.
It's called "initial observation".
It will give him something to compare his findings with later.
Notice the subject's body posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone is a regular foot-tapping person so that you do not falsely accuse him of lying just because he starts tapping his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But consider it only as a warning sign, not as proof of a lie.
People who tell lies may stop moving their upper half when trying to remember their fictional story, may turn their shoe to the door, lean out, change their posture dramatically, or show "relief at the end of the conversation" - excessively relaxed breathing and changing position when confession is difficult.
Interviewers often give the false signal that the interview is over, just to see what relief will be like when it's over.
Also, notice the language of the subject.
There's a famous story about how Scott Peterson once mispronounced and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which sparked a nationwide search for her body.
Lying individuals may also say in moderation, "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very subtle.
Someone may use a lot of "mild language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... as I know... to the best of my knowledge".
Such a response may not reveal much of the facts, and it is often just another warning sign.
There is no magic to uncover every lie, but you can learn the skills to detect a lie.
With these skills, a person will have a better chance of avoiding being exposed to a liar and a cheat in his personal and professional life.
A controversial oil pipeline project is to be diverted after the threat of delayed U.S. government approval
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico - turning unions against each other but reassuring environmentalists - the company in charge of building the pipeline announced it was willing to re-route the project to get things moving again.
TransCanada announced Monday night that it would move a planned pipeline route from the environmentally sensitive Sandhills in Nebraska, and is confident the project will still be approved.
The company announced this decision at a press conference at the Nebraska Government Headquarters.
TransCanada's Alex Pourbax claims that the company is confident that the pipeline will eventually be approved, even though it will lead a different route.
This announcement comes after the State Department announced last week that it was delaying a decision on federal permits for the project, from which it would conduct a study of possible alternate routes that would avoid impacting the Sandhills of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast underground water reservoir.
"This is a real step forward", Republican Representative Lee Terry of Nebraska told Fox News.
A new environmental assessment ordered by the State Department would likely delay any decision until 2013, a year after next year's election, but officials deny any political role in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as a request from the State Department and expressed his support.
A 1,700-mile pipeline will connect Canada and the Gulf of Mexico.
It carries 700,000 barrels of oil a day from Alberta to refineries in Texas.
This is a six-state road.
The project is absolutely hated by environmentalists, but loved by the work crews, who estimate that 20,000 new jobs will be created by working on the pipeline.
However, legislators in Nebraska opposed this plan and considered legislation to force the company to withhold access to the Sand Hills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the main source of drinking water and irrigation.
An existing environmental impact study commissioned by the State Department found that the project would have only a minor negative environmental impact, but an energy industry source said the inspector general from the State Department had ordered a review of the entire process of the original study, focusing mainly on two issues.
One was whether a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was an adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, had a conflict of interest in the program.
Another was whether the company that was hired to conduct the original study was not selected inappropriately because it had ties to TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle is accused of making a toddler throw up in fear.
A New York family says singer Patti LaBelle stormed into the lobby of their Manhattan home and scared their daughter so badly that she threw up in fear.
The performance of the hit singer "Lady Marmalade" so frightened 18-month-old Genevieve Monk that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disturbances" and "increased fear of strangers", her family claims in a lawsuit filed in Manhattan Superior Court.
