The economic slowdown caused by the unfavorable climate
During the first year of the government of Maria López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability in Sinaloa increased, foreign investment declined and with it the economy
The year 2011 will go down in Sinaloa's economic history as the first year of the self-styled government of change, led by Maria López Valdez, which brought with it high expectations for economic progress, but due to unfavourable climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth was recorded and even major indicators of economic development declined.
The low temperatures in February have caused millions of agricultural losses, limited the growth of the national economy, and led to a 3.6% decline in economic activity in the first half of this year, with agriculture falling by a historic 31.16%, which has also affected other economic sectors.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares of cultivated land were damaged, of which 78,03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21,07% were partially damaged.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a steady increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state's unemployment rate recorded an increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents were unemployed in Sinaloa, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, the average unemployment rate continued to rise, reaching a value of 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
According to Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the measures that have been implemented at the level of public policy.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is linked to a variety of factors, including a loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation passed by Congress to combat money laundering, and it is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn, invest or use them", he said.
Stop the migration
López Cervantes said that demographics also contributed to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work in the United States has decreased, partly because of the difficulty of entry and partly because even if these people get across the border, it is difficult for them to find work.
Unreliable
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is also worsened by the growing unreliability prevailing in the area of working conditions.
In addition to unemployment and unreliability, there are other labour market features such as low wages.The administrative territory has the lowest wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa State was 5,352 pesos as of September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, 2011 also saw the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years.According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment in the period from January to June amounted to USD 630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74% compared to USD 5,143,312 in the same period of the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government reports investments of PTE 17 280 million per year, mainly in service enterprises.
Other liabilities
In July, the state government requested the state congress to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. As of November, no gains from debt had been recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to business representatives, the first year of the government of Maria López Valdés showed the lack of management skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformative Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of coordination between the will of the various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The economic development in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year. In 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, there was a lack of coordination of our efforts and especially the proper and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let's hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Loredo López said events like frost at the beginning of the year have halted the state's economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic performance was caused by a number of events, including freezes.One of the main consequences was the slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to regain momentum to achieve acceptable levels of movement of processes, products and services.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The Work Ahead
Coparmex's chairman stressed the importance of setting a vision for the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there has been some progress in economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term plan", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy management.
"There are elements to say that the government is trying to be friendly, I can say that the work has been done and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead", he said.
