Despite the promise of the State authorities to transfer these resources, he said that a request had been sent to Armando Villarreal, Secretary of Administration and Finance, to expedite the procedure and that the corresponding percentage had arrived as soon as possible.
"They were supposed to give us 12 million, and even though the year is coming to an end, we haven't received a single peso yet".
The Court approves the "end of analogue broadcasting in Mexico in 2015"
The replacement of analogue signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice (SCJN) has rejected a constitutional lawsuit brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against a presidential decree that seeks to speed up the so-called "turning off of analog signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021.
A minority of four ministers, including the court's president, Juana Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón did not overstep his authority when he issued a decree outlining the steps leading to the transition to digital terrestrial television.
The action brought by the Senate was therefore dismissed on the ground that the qualified majority of eight votes required for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree was not obtained, and that the decree thus remains in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all matters relating to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel).
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported a constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight the decree.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion on the proposal, which is also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal that the federal executive cannot structure measures to prepare the public administration through general standards.
"I don't think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory authority", he said, noting that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, related to better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would be to delay the benefits of digitalisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, as digitalisation is not only technical but also "touches on economic, social, political and national security issues".
He stressed that these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the digital switchover, and did so through their governments, despite having highly specialised technical bodies at their disposal.
He argued that it was impossible for the government to enforce the laws of the legislature in the administration by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent interfered with the powers of Congress.
In Michoacán, they're analyzing the possibility of adding "voice by voice"
According to the PREP data, the difference between first and second place in the governor's race is less than 27 percent.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" appeared in this year's election in Michoacán, where according to data released by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent, and that is without counting 879 votes out of a total of 6074 electoral districts.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral authority approved a series of measures to harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially ratified its political constitution, nor its State Electoral Code or Electoral Justice Act, as the state congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this election period, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel failed to publish them within the deadline set in the Official Gazette Law, saying he had some objections to them.
On 9 November, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) settled a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature, declaring the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "null and void" because he has no right "to approve or veto them".
When asked about the possibility of a vote-by-vote count, María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the General Council of the IEM, it would be possible for both the partial and the total count to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral parcels, will be possible under the following conditions: the election results are not in agreement; there is no record of the counting of votes and the calculation in the relevant box or it is not available to the President concerned; or there have been errors and manifest irregularities in the election results.
In addition, the total vote count at all polling stations will be possible if there is evidence that the difference between the potential winner and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that proposed the candidate in second place appears at the beginning of the session.
The total vote will also be counted if, after a proper count, the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, and whenever there is an express request from the political party whose candidate finished second, in which case the partially counted ballots will be discarded.
It should be noted that this is the situation in Morelia, where, according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is less than 0,16%, although 129 of the 923 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
His last will and testament
His ashes will be scattered in the Zapaliname Mountains, family confirmed.
The remains of Felipe Bacio Cortés were transported to his hometown of Saltillo on Sunday night for a solemn ceremony and a funeral mass on Monday.
According to the family, the lieutenant colonel's last wish was that his ashes be scattered in the Zapaliname mountains.
After receiving the highest honors, along with the other victims of the accident, the Bacio Cortés family returned to the capital of Coahuila aboard a Mexican Air Force plane, where they and their closest friends attended the ceremony at Campo Marte.
At noon, the colonel's ashes were brought to the chapel on Nazario Ortiz Garza Street, where family and friends gathered.
At 5:30 p.m., a farewell party was held at the Saltillo Institute of Technology, organized by his former high school classmates and members of the football team, of which Felipe Bacio was a member during his senior year.
"He wanted to return to Saltilla and his wish was that his ashes be scattered in the Zapalinama mountains, as he always told his family and friends", said Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister.
She said the lieutenant colonel had fulfilled all his wishes, was at the top of his game, "a wonderful man, an extraordinary father, a son, a loving brother who lived for his family".
Felipe Bacio Cortés left the town of Saltillo at a very young age and enrolled in the Colegio del Aire flight school in Zapopan, Jalisco.
Some people didn't believe it because they said he even drove a truck, but he always went after his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio remembers him as a very good man, "he had barely arrived in Saltillo, the whole family wanted to see him, like when he brought Martha Sahagún to Saltillo".
The young man even recalls that when he was seven years old, he went to Zapopan for his uncle's graduation, so he believes he died doing what he loved most in life - flying an airplane.
They gave him his final farewell
Felipe Bacio Cortés, Lieutenant Colonel of the Mexican Air Force, and I said goodbye to all the honors that Governor Jorge Torres López, the citizens and the government of the state, the Mexican Army through the Sixth Military Zone, the Mexican Air Force itself, the officials and students of the Technological High School in Saltillo, where he graduated in 1985 and where he excelled in both studies and sports.
Bacio Cortés died in a helicopter crash a few days ago, along with Secretary of State José Francisco Blake Mora and six other people, all state officials.
At 18:05 the remains of Bacio Cortese, a native of Saltillo, arrived (cremated) to be handed over to the Mexican Air Force through a funeral service led by Major Jaime Martinez, where the family, his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, mother, siblings and other relatives, students and teachers had gathered.
Three abandoned bodies were found at Caderey's NL estate.
A few hours before the discovery, military officials presented to the media 11 individuals who had been detained in the area for crimes related to organized crime.
The bodies of three men, shot in different parts of the body and head, were found on an abandoned property in Cadereyta Jiménez, Nuevo León.
The discovery was made a mile down the road from Cadereyta to Santiago, at the level of an area known as El Castillo.
People who moved about in these places noticed that the beige-coffee-fenced hut had an occasional open door.
When they looked inside, about ten feet [3 m] away, they saw three dead bodies and immediately alerted the authorities.
One of the subjects was wearing a yellow sports shirt and dark cotton pants, not a shoe, and next to him was a man also wearing a white striped sports shirt.
A few feet away, the body of another man dressed in a red sweatshirt and blue cotton pants.
All three of them were lying face down.
Based on the data we got from the scene, all three people were probably killed at another location because no bullets were found.
On the fence of the cabin, messages were found addressed by one organized crime group to another, as well as a number of bullet marks on both the building and the door.
11 suspects have been arrested in Cadereyta
The Secretary of National Defence has identified 11 individuals, including juveniles, who were members of a criminal group that operated mainly in the Cadereyta area and is linked to kidnappings, murders, stalking and illegal burials.
