The new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that is keeping the country above the brink of economic catastrophe.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that has kept the country above the brink of economic catastrophe and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The presidential palace issued a statement saying that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he can form a government.
He is expected to introduce a government made up of mostly technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in an attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to get through this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were being overcome.
"The framework is now well defined", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less time than usual, while Italy struggles to fight a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough package of austerity measures demanded by European leaders, the only way to restore Italy's shattered credibility.
Monti is under intense pressure to hurry up, as market instability has pushed the interest rate on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above the 7% mark, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to seek bailouts.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Confindustria, the Italian employers' organisation, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe this government is the last chance to get Italy out of this critical situation.
Monti's hopes for success have been greatly boosted by the support of the PDL of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to produce good results", Angelina Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because up to this point, a number of its members had opposed the government with a technocratic majority, which Monti is forming.
Support for Parliament
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in this effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could spell disaster.
Monti opened talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organisations.
The round of negotiations will end Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, which allowed for very rapid progress in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline late last week when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields have returned to critical levels in response to uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is €1.8 trillion, would be beyond the current financial reserves of the euro area.
Monti has said his government should remain in power until the next election, which is scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will give him time only to implement reforms, and then call early elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this government must be composed of only experts to get Italy out of the difficulties it has run into due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicated the attempt to include both political figures in the government.
