The quintet has included the country in their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary.
"A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to play one of their best shows at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We've been waiting for over 20 years, but the band itself says that for them, the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is on the South American continent as part of their 20th anniversary tour and will make a unique stopover in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
He's performing at the National Stadium this evening at 7:30 with the angelic band The X and the folk musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample of the interview, which you can find in full on La Nación's website.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true, Pearl Jam is playing in Costa Rica.
A trip to Costa Rica is also our dream come true.
This is only our second time in South and Central America, and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, and it's a beautiful country, and I believe we can stay here for a few days.
So we're very excited to bring you our music.
I ask because the band is literally adored here, and the fans are having these days of preparation very intense.
What do you say to your most ardent supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took so long.
Some people are already talking about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the greatest shows we've put on in the last 21 years were created in a matter of weeks.
We did some great shows in Sao Paulo, and we're hoping that's what's gonna get us in shape for the Costa Rica show.
We're really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle, and for both of those things, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico, and these are the best places to surf, and that's how we learned about Costa Rica from people who love surfing.
Looking back on your tour, you put on a great show with a lot of songs.
What are you planning for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, there's no limit to what we can do.
We're gonna try to put on the best variety show we can, try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good, diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of it's because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everybody likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played in a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about them.
It makes the show more interesting for us, and I think that's why it's more interesting for people.
This tour is to celebrate 20 years of your artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure you do.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined being in a big rock band and staying in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much we've been given and we're moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to see the places we've always wanted to see.
We couldn't have ended up better.
What did it mean to you to be a major part of the birth of the grunge genre?
We've always been honored to be part of this group of great people.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement starts out with a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
Occasionally a group will be formed in a town, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to appear in one town at a time.
We're proud and honored to be part of a Seattle band.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're lucky to have all these friends and we're honored to be part of this movement that started in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is a lot longer than the usual band length.
I think, first, we're all lucky to still be in this world, and second, it's partly because we're constantly interested in each other.
We're all close friends, and because of that, we've been able to open up musical paths that allow everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we respect each other's music, and I think it couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, but your success allows you to do whatever you like.
How do you find the balance?
As we grew older, it became easier and easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came here for the music, you remember that you have to respect the music and what you've given it, and you can't get carried away by being famous, rock stars.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something great at first.
We were in the band for three years and never released an album until after Andy died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long, and the most important thing is that even today, we're still friends with Bruce and Greg who started out in the band with us, and when I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how amazing he was, how I laughed with him, and it was always a joy to work with him, laugh with him, talk about music or football and so much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss her very much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as your forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with some suggestions, and we liked this band the best, so we were curious to see what Las Robertas had to offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Eddie Vedder, so I don't know.
He's singing it, and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who's your bass player?
A lot of people.
The first people to attack me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them, I could talk all night about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam keep grunge going even though it's out of fashion?
I think we've all always felt a little detached from the word grunge.
When I think of grunge, I think of the bands I've mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out around the same time, and if music is still relevant today, that's great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music than ever before.
At first, your music was a little somber, but now it's more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a couple of songs on the new album that are a little bit more light-hearted, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very bleak, although they can sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and you have a trauma in your life, you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs to me are just that.
