Peru:
Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized at a public hospital on Tuesday for tests for muscle loss in his lower extremities, his attending physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is currently under medical control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases in three days to determine why he is in pain and losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that he thought Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, but the former president himself does not want to be pardoned because he feels innocent.
He had four operations for tongue cancer, lost 60 pounds [18 kg], and had other ailments, including severe erosive gastritis, a pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in his legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by an army killing squad operating illegally in the first years of his rule.
Musician on a visit to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to seek to expand trade between the two nations and to discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday, the first meeting of a major visit to Mexico by political, business and Uruguayan community leaders, the program was announced by the Uruguayan presidential office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political issues between the two countries", the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to back Uruguay in a dispute with France that has erupted after French President Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to expel countries that continued to be tax havens from the international community, a statement that drew a negative response from Uruguay and consultation with its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been the chair of the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful developing and developed countries, and has signed an information-sharing agreement with the Latin American country to prevent double taxation since January this year.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has been working to concretise fiscal exchange agreements in order to get off the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) 'blacklist' of countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of tax cooperation.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
The bearded installer runs in 3D thanks to Super Mario 3D Land
For over 25 years, Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but has never appeared in 3D before: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which is coming to stores around the world this month, was designed from the ground up to take advantage of all the features offered by the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows you to play 3D games without the need for glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to tell stereoscopy how to work without glasses", said Nintendo of Spain press officer Omar Álvarez during a video game presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game created specifically for this medium", because up to that point successful films like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of already existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesperson stated that in addition to being 3D, Super Mario 3D Land is an "accessible" video game that allows for a fast and smooth gameplay experience.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple", whose task is to attract less skilled users.
Once you've passed this level, you can proceed to the "second round" of the game, which is more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose between real-time "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in 3D to overcome various challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This new arrival of Super Maria in 3D also includes a return to the handheld console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo plays to the tune of those who follow the saga, repeating the successful formula of the previous installments, which is that the bearded man's plumber will have to go through dangerous minefields to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find new moves, surroundings, disguises and even among enemies, a "playful" Luigi will also appear.
Colom has approved Portilla's extradition to the United States.
President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has moved forward with the extradition of former President Alfonso Portilla, who is being held in the United States on charges of conspiracy to launder $70 million.
This concludes a process that was intended to allow Guatemala to respond to a request by a northern country to extradite Portilla to stand trial.
At a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was in line with the independence of the judiciary and the executive and that he was aware that the criminal court had already ordered extradition.
He has assured that he has not "interfered" in court decisions during his term and has authorised all extraditions that have come to his desk.
In addition to Portilla, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and aggravated assault and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colomo's move marks the execution step after all judicial and constitutional means were exhausted to prosecute the former president, who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala is resolved and human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzling $120 million from the Department of Defense during his presidency, a process that preceded extradition, but the State Department appealed, bringing the case back into play.
