Yesterday, city police also cleared a building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police arrived at building 35 on Rue de Montréal after being called by neighbors who saw four people enter the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountains?
The architects have come together to write a lawsuit that involves more than a fee controversy.
The municipal tender for 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of the Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The flyer defined the mountain as a large park in metropolitan Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the CMB disappeared in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona, as the Catalan capital is one of the few that does not orient on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with the wild boar instead of Yogi the Bear.
This was the position until September, when the city council announced a mega competition of 16 entries for the same number of entrances to Collserola.
The gate, of course, is more of a recording of the idea of a park.
Either that, or someone's trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organisational point of view and from a reflection on the city, this question becomes a central theme for all Barcelona architects.
It's as old-fashioned as when two members of this ancient caste, chosen at a meeting in an elevator, shake hands.
And it was this act that produced one of the rare coincidences between the thinking of three Barcelona architects and a prominent university professor.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the competition is justified.
According to Roldan, once the question of the Gulf side was raised, the 'mountain side' 'must' be discussed as well, so that Ildefons Cerda's speech on green apples was not completed.
"We must assume that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex", said the architect, for whom the name 'Gates to Collserola' is a 'lexicological trap': we must not think of them 'as entrances to the park, but rather as the demarcation of zones where it is possible to act'.
Modol, like Roldan and Bayonne, with experience in the world of urban planning, describes the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The danger arising from the "uncertainty that the public space project presents today" after the experience of the 1980s, which had its swan song in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very definition of where it should be built.
"To define something is to take the next step", which is basically to go one step further.
"The new urban planning and planning tools must be kept in mind, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (GMP)) can cause a real disaster".
In a more detailed analysis, Modol considers that the Collserola valley slope can be 'considered a park' but the Barcelona area cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there was already work done by the Patronat de Collserola which 'must not end up in the garbage', although he welcomed the fact that the town hall offered his board to intervene in the project 'from the first moment'.
He also understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of loophole that allows architects to engage in the debate, but "doubts" that it should be this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should be just tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the game its name is complex because the tender documents lack Collserola's global vision: "16 tenders have been announced covering the whole mountain-sea axis, but there is no longitudinal study that looks at and understands the area as a whole".
That makes him, at least, the one who signed up for all 16 auditions.
Otherwise, the design of one gate may conflict with the architect's concept and definition of the adjacent gate.
In his view, the town hall should ensure that the zone immediately above the Ronda de Dalt is provided with facilities along its entire length to ensure a smooth transition between the town and the green.
