Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome has provided details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people.
The Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (SCT) said the results of the investigation into the crash that killed the Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people show that the helicopter crashed into the ground with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, the Secretary of Communications and Transportation, said that before the plane took off, the pilot had noted that the climatic conditions of the flight allowed.
"The parts that emerge indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings tangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 persons and therefore met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
It further stated that, based on the investigation carried out at the impact site, no components were found on the ground.
"The search revealed that the plane's parts were not elsewhere, so the plane hit the mainland intact.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, meeting all passenger requirements.
The terrain is inclined seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at this time, it is most important to get results as quickly as possible, but the investigation could take months or even a year.
Gilberto Lopez Meyer, director general of airport and emergency services, said the helicopter was traveling at cruise speed at the time of the crash and the crash occurred on soft ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis that the accident was a routine flight operation", he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome outlined six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was conducted under visual flight rules, which means that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
The weather conditions:
AICM reports indicate adequate take-off conditions, according to which the aircraft is moving towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico, there were visible layers of low-level clouds.
Routes selected:
It is likely that the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility into the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Location of impact.
The crash coordinates and the helicopter's last radar record match, so it's likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of flight path prior to the crash.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information we have at this time allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The scatter plot of the plane debris indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of impact.
No fire or explosion was reported.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident to indicate that there was an explosion or fire.
The latest investigation indicates that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the field work, aircraft debris was found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet, the terrain is steep, the slope of the slope ranges from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of what is believed to be a breakdown along the route.
The information provided elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have made contact with the ground at several locations.
After a thorough search of the accident site, no remains of the helicopter were found in an area larger than the designated area, which reinforces the belief that the impact occurred while the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has begun research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for child and adolescent obesity.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to identify the gene that causes obesity in children and adolescents.
In a report, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the 21st Century National Health Centre Specialist Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without permits, can also get involved in the research by visiting the participating IMSS sports centers in the Valle de México, where tests will be given to youths every Sunday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research began at Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and since October 8th, the same activity is also being carried out at Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children have been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to determine the components and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people aged between six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that every Saturday, all participants are given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels, and genes (an attempt to identify genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that the research reflects health officials' concerns about the alarming increase in childhood obesity.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and a 47% increase in girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He said that one reason for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of a country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of his genetic makeup of Native Americans, 30% of European and 5% of African, reflected in the genes responsible for diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn off excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the children's condition, which can reveal whether they are known to be overweight or obese.
He noted that even the presence of dark wrinkles (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential, and doctors give it in writing to parents, explaining all the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent their children from getting the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using public transportation instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by high calorie intake, i.e. higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) high in fat and protein, and genetic load, which is the subject of this research.
There will be no cracks in the asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, creates modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving was properly maintained, the nearly 200,000 potholes in the Valle de México Metropolitan area would not need to be repaired after each rainy season, notes Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who added that if the construction and maintenance of the paving were adequate, the potholes would be significantly reduced or even eliminated.
In his talk on the Technological Cause of Potholes, which he gave during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that his laboratory is developing modified polymer asphalt, which should produce a mixture with similar properties to asphalt but greater mechanical strength at both low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve functionality and reduce the formation of ditches.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltenes, and low molecular weight molecules called maltenes, which together give asphalt its characteristic viscoelastic character.
The viscoelasticity of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, has a high viscosity at 120 degrees, and is almost solid at 50 degrees, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in streets is not uniform but varies during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, noted a chemical engineer.
A chemistry scientist observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Between the topmost layers is an asphalt veneer, made up of small pebbles that are covered in asphalt and then compacted.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When vehicles pass by or when pressure is generated, it is possible to distribute the forces in the pavement well.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, says a chemical engineer.
He added that the final layer, called the mantle, is made up of fine stone, or sand, also covered with asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the vehicle tyres, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and must ensure friction on the road.
Since the load will be high as part of the paving, the cover must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken with the material of which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to be kept in mind.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inward and is difficult to get out, softening all layers of the pavement and creating crevices.
He explained that the first thing that happens when the cladding is damaged is the asphalt insert, which is not damaged all at once but is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first sign of damage by proper maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle loads are another important factor in the formation of pits, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must be consistent with the vehicle load and must ensure that this load is not exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that much work remains to be done on asphalt and that research is still in its infancy, such as asphalt emulsions, which are already available in other countries and allow for easy repair of cracks without the need for high temperatures.
