The government of the grand coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to inscribe a "golden rule" of fiscal policy in the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's rating by the AAA.
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision at the end of the Ministerial Conference, at a time when Austria's public debt, at 74.6%, is well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year", argued the multichancellor and foreign minister, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
