Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma.
If there is one issue that cannot be tackled on the basis of short-term thinking or under emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It's natural that the election meeting is an opportunity to think about these contributions and the place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are now seven billion people on the planet, but demographic trends will cause the demand for electricity to double between now and 2050, unless we want to deprive a significant part of the world's population of this vital component of life.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil fuels will have to be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity, while not forgetting the need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that is currently missing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident has no effect on any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany is alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
This is not the case for Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find another source capable of replacing itself, or for Switzerland, which considers it appropriate to build only state-of-the-art power plants.
In contrast, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name a few, are continuing their efforts.
The United States decided to expand its fleet by one unit after Fukushima by rebuilding one plant that was interrupted by the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German renewable energy model is ever presented as an example, reality is contrary.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in the rise in electricity prices, the increased energy dependence on gas imported, especially from Russia, the sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal-fired power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves our consideration.
The European champion in wind power, which generates 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which make Denmark's CO2 emissions and electricity prices 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and guaranteeing the survival of industry on national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a sharp increase in the price of electricity, making illusory the beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, as well as being fundamentally opposed to this energy, as opinion polls show.
Recall that our country's energy policy has allowed us to build a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 secondary jobs.
The strong export sector attracts a large number of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these SMEs and lose EUR 6 billion a year which the country earns from the export of nuclear equipment and services.
What power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to operate for 60 years while its manufacturer was scheduled to go out of business?
In solving the energy equation, one must admit that there is no magic source for energy production, and indeed no evil one.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy facilities by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a State Agency for Nuclear Safety, which carries out a strict and transparent supervision of the existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of the new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In the last 50 years, the nuclear industry has seen three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island that occurred in normal operating conditions and was left without human casualties and environmental consequences.
The Chernobyl tragedy was caused by reactor design and inexcusable human error.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the disaster was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, killing tens of thousands.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident as it did from the two before it.
The result of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers is that the EPR reactor is a concept capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While all interested parties consider it a good idea, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to AREVA's and EDF's competitors and would pave the way for them to take a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solution for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogma and machinery dominate a debate so crucial to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the overcrowding of police, courts and administrations subject to a policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of 'land of human rights' of which France boasts.
Recently, it was administrative harassment of foreign students that became a hot topic when the interior minister (see Libération of 23 May) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses".
But so far, it's rarely been discussed in terms of economics.
It must be said that there is a fairly broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
The right was set to the tune in 1976 by Jacques Chirac, who said that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with 2 million migrant workers", and the left by Michel Rocard, who said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of French territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by the right and the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity we're charged to extend to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities when he claims that joint development will solve our 'migration problem'.
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may be valid in elections, but it's very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in their recently published book, Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, page 352: There is broad consensus among professionals on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration is crippling growth and hurting jobs.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they can replace French workers, especially those with lower skills, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that in fact immigrants are much more a complement than a substitute for French workers, by taking up jobs in sectors with a shortage of workers.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not enough to fill the vacancies.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty in working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity between the French and migrants is causing the arrival of immigrants to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would lead to a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And it does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (the high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, on average at 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organisation, for example, estimates that in Germany, one immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will contribute a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of EUR 150000 to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his term, said he wanted to "pull the wool over the teeth" to make up for the missing percentage of growth.
The teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, we have to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and also very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, because although it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it has experienced the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece during the 20th century.
Some people may have believed that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to conduct the election and conduct it in the most direct way possible.
But we've known since Napoleon that it was about ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an 'instrument of oppression', as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, the organization of the separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also and has been since the beginning of time a crisis of politics and democracy.
Admitting the mistake of the Greek yes-no referendum will have a double revealing value in this respect: revealing the need for a major return to political power, but also revealing the disturbing sense of its impossibility, its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is, the front lines of the Democratic fight have shifted today, and many of the Republican fighters are no longer firing in the right direction.
We can't get anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organised as needed and disorganized.
White in front of a European absolute monarch or leaping into the empty depths of nationalism with your feet tied: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a joint, full, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal -- we wouldn't even know where to start the list, anyway -- because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, which is suffering from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its nations.
The European project of democratic sovereignty must be brought back to the forefront.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce their debt burden, get rid of market rule and invest for the future.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, or else lead to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for a European economic government.
Be my guest.
But to think that without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such citizens, would be another madness and a new dead end.
We must take on a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" republicans.
A revolution in the interests of the people could not have done that.
This lesson continues.
We must build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This can only be done by building a Europe that is more politically democratic and truly European democratic sovereign.
Let us become Europeans to build Europe.
Contactless chip cards are spreading
In an optimistic atmosphere, the World Chip Fair opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris.
According to Eurosmart, the year 2011 should end with a rise in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM phones) of 11% to over 6 billion units.
The most portable is the contactless technology segment, which allows you to pay on public transport or make purchases simply by bringing your card close to the reader.
