The terror front stretches from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram.
Long-standing suspicions of links to the terrorist group Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQMI) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's deputy foreign minister Abdelkader Messahel even admitted that Algeria had now "gained certainty".
"The way the two organizations operate and intelligence reports show that there is a great deal of cooperation between them", he explained without elaborating.
It seems Paris has similar analyses.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January 2010 could help illuminate the connecting bridges.
After being kidnapped by AQMI members from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the following day at the same time as several of their captors in an operation carried out by French special forces.
In the rubble after the raid, French and Nigerian investigators were to find several phones with chips belonging to terrorists.
The Terrorist Axis
The analysis of the calls made leads to several individuals in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two figures: one that leads to a Nigerian long-time resident of Maiduguri, the northern city that is the birthplace of Boko Haram, and another that leads to a man said to be close to AQIM and the sect.
"It's progress, but it's definitely going to take more convincing evidence before we start talking about operational cooperation between AQIM and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys outside financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more active", mildly remarks Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian investigator.
In recent months, this 'support' has become increasingly evident in the development and manifestations of Boko Haram or its operational procedures, which now involve human casualties or increasingly complex explosive devices of the same design as those used by AQIM.
The international community, led by Washington, has since put pressure on Nigeria to address the problems posed by Boko Haram.
In fact, the Nigerian authorities have long considered the group a community of enlightened mystics of little interest.
A quick success
The Boko Haram sect was founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, school and fundamentalist Muhammad Yusuf.Boko Haram, which means "Western education is a sin" in Hausa, endorses the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, such a connection is a quick success.
The sect is politicised and demands strict adherence to Islamic Sharia law, while its followers are waging a war against the central government.
These people are first targeting churches, bars and government offices.
In 2009, Boko Haram supporters became extraordinarily active and increased their attacks on police stations.
The government's response is still the same as usual.
The army surrounds the city, and the result is 800 dead.
The founder of the sect, Mohammed Yusuf, is captured and killed in prison.
Since then, the group has been radicalizing and leaving its base in the north.
On Christmas 2010, he carried out an assassination in Jos, killing 80 people, followed by another in the capital Abuja.
In June, it's Abuja again, where Boko Haram attacks the police headquarters in their first suicide attack.
And in August, the local UN office will be the first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which should run from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now a concern for all security experts.
Now that al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb has surrounded Mali and the Iger and Somali al-Shabab movement are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat to the continent.
Last week in Nigeria, in an interview with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé said that France was on alert and ready to "transmit all information".
The world by presidential candidates
When it comes to issues like China, Iran, or helping Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry are all out to simplify and out to ignore.
