Nord Stream, the new port of entry for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which links Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been put into operation.
They must supply the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the occasion properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new undersea gas pipeline that will directly connect Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have jointly turned the control valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
This new pipeline will bring an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with the federal state of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed by the end of 2012, will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, an amount equivalent to all French consumption.
And there's already talk of a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction is a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being piped through the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the ability to pressure Russia by threatening to cut off its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the 1939 occupation of Poland.
It means to say that this is a politically sensitive subject.
Western Europe's support for this Russian project has given it greater security of purchasing power.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created a rift between Europeans from the East and the West.
Russia barely managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-consuming Western states whose gas fields are running out.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically", François Fillon said at the inauguration ceremony, demonstrating the political and economic importance of large gas contracts.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a major technical feat.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel with a concrete cover to protect it from the anchorage of sea vessels.
It lies on the seabed at an average depth of 200 metres.
The construction of the bridge was to avoid the minefields of World War II.
"For safety reasons, almost 100 of them had to be removed or destroyed", says Nord Stream spokesman Jens Müller.
It was also necessary to step up measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, uninterrupted by valves or maintenance stations along its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it, as the Swedes were only reluctant to see the Russian state company permanently established on their coast.
"In the event of a malfunction, we stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas line will escape into the air.
But this is considered unlikely by the builders, since the weld was designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The outer pipe is checked by a ship-drawn underwater robot, while the inner pipe is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device, one meter in diameter, is inserted into the inside of a pipe and pressed with gas.
It shall provide precise information on any deformation of metal parts after the three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s.
The long-range pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply provided by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at takeoff and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains with Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as Gasunie and GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transmission capacity to this company for a renewable contract of five years.
'Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the actual amount of gas transported,' explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
The investment costs for GDF Suez thus amounted to EUR 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be recovered, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin on a sandy coastline with pine forests.
The 15 feet high valves form the gas outlet.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - the branded notebook
Moleskine, an Italian company founded 50 years ago, wants to bring back the joy of writing.
It brings a fragrance of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves, white and aged.
After all, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born back in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, a consultant working for the company at the time, takes charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old moleskin production technique, which is used for example to treat the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists well into the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from the clandestine production of the early years when only 3,000 minutes were made.
Moleskine is exported across the Italian border to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a virtual portrait of the buyer because the notebook will interest businessmen as much as students or professionals.
The Moleskin notebook's image is that its owners are cosmopolitan, cultured, open-minded people.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, has grown to almost 100 and, since 2008, has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks to bookstores and through the FNAC chain to small boutiques in the city centers where he has been able to assert his identity.
"We followed the spirit of the times and the need for new writing, despite the rapid development of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "The Order", where architects or artists display their notebook.
In August, she also presented new leopard-like notebooks at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine profits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases... The brand expands to a whole range of media.
An enviable success: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by investment funds SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers so high?
Some 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today marks the 15th week of employment for the handicapped.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of disabled people unemployed is still twice the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the general population.
Is that depressing?
"No", stresses Éric Blanchet, director general of the association Adapt, which organises the Employment Week for the Disabled".
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher".
"However, much remains to be done".
It must be said that there are still numerous obstacles to the entry into employment of disabled people who are unemployed.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They are low-skilled: 80% have no high school diploma and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is very high: 53% for the handicapped compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and which are 'the core of the problem', according to Christian Grapin, Director-General of the Tremplin Association, which was set up in 1992 to help enterprises recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
What remains unspeakable are ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur pour la Cité found that managers surveyed had"a low level of knowledge about disabled people" with"an exaggerated idea of people in wheelchairs and mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures, which date back to 2008, show a level of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organisation charged with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of 'fined' undertakings and the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to EUR 480 million).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put a lot of pressure on businesses", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large companies".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
"What a stroke of luck".
